          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="577" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821144?width=860&amp;height=577" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林长期以来对人工智能技术很感兴趣，他定期与参与人工智能研究的谷歌员工会面。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JUNG YEON-JE/​​法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/miles-kruppa" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈尔斯·克鲁帕</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪帕·西塔拉曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 10:10（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林重返工作岗位。</p><p>近几个月来，这位亿万富翁每周都会访问这家科技巨头位于加州山景城的办公室，通常每周三到四天，与研究人员一起努力开发该公司的下一个大型人工智能系统。</p><p>知情人士称，布林去年年底参加了谷歌办公室有关人工智能的会议，但他参与的频率和强度有所增加。他的新立场与他在 2019 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sundar-pichai-to-replace-larry-page-as-ceo-of-alphabet-11575409229?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞去</a>母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="company-name">Alphabet</a>高管职务后采取的相对不干涉的态度发生了显着变化。</p><p>他与一组研究人员密切合作，构建了谷歌期待已久的人工智能模型 Gemini。他们讨论了诸如“损失曲线”之类的技术问题，这是一种衡量人工智能程序随时间推移表现的方法，布林还每周与谷歌员工就新的人工智能研究进行讨论。知情人士称，他还干预人事事务，例如聘用受欢迎的研究人员。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，布林在谷歌的影响力增加反映了人工智能的关键时刻以及他对这项技术的长期兴趣。谷歌是该技术的先驱，但在将其转化为新产品方面比竞争对手慢。</p><p>随着 Meta Platforms 等公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-and-microsoft-team-up-to-distribute-new-ai-software-for-commercial-use-c4f7b634?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近推出的新产品</a>，人工智能研究领域的竞争正在加剧。谷歌<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-tries-to-catch-up-to-rivals-like-openai-as-they-release-viral-apps-11674828418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了产品开发速度，</a>以应对去年发布的 ChatGPT，这是一款由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>支持的研究公司 OpenAI 开发的人工智能聊天机器人，可以流畅地响应一系列书面查询。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820793?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌创始人谢尔盖·布林和拉里·佩奇从斯坦福大学博士生起就一直在一起工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·内格尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Gemini 是 Google 尝试构建的<a href="https://blog.google/technology/ai/google-palm-2-ai-large-language-model/" target="_blank" class="icon none">通用人工智能</a>程序，可以与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/openai-rolls-out-updated-version-of-viral-chatbot-chatgpt-f03fea27?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OpenAI 的 GPT-4 模型</a>相媲美，该模型为 ChatGPT 的付费版本提供支持。据知情人士透露，负责该项目的谷歌高管德米斯·哈萨比斯 (Demis Hassabis) 在最近的一次全公司会议上告诉员工，该项目将于今年晚些时候推出。</p><p> 49 岁的布林于 1998 年与拉里·佩奇 (Larry Page) 一起创立了谷歌，他们在斯坦福大学攻读博士时共同进行了网络搜索研究。</p><p>虽然布林近年来偶尔出现在谷歌总部，但他的注意力主要集中在飞艇和新形式的灾难援助等外部利益上，以及捐赠部分巨额财富的努力。根据 S&amp;P Capital IQ 的数据，他是 Alphabet 的第二大个人股东，仅次于 Page，所持股份价值接近 900 亿美元。</p><p>自从谷歌在 5 月份的年度开发者大会上宣布一系列人工智能产品以来，Alphabet 的股价已经上涨了 10% 以上，其中包括新版本的核心搜索引擎，该引擎提供了冗长的摘要并邀请后续问题。这一涨幅与竞争对手微软的股价和更广泛的纳斯达克综合指数大致一致。</p><p>知情人士称，布林大部分时间都在新建的查尔斯顿东大楼里与山景城的人工智能研究人员坐在一起，该大楼距离谷歌公司园区原来的中心仅几步之遥。谷歌和 Alphabet 的首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊 (Sundar Pichai) 也在大楼内设有办公室。</p><p>四年前，当创始人辞去日常职务并将皮查伊提拔为 Alphabet 首席执行官时，他们表示将定期与他交谈并提供“建议和关爱，但不会每天唠叨”。他们仍然控制着 Alphabet 的多数投票权，并与皮查伊一起担任执行董事会委员会成员。</p><p>据一位了解皮查伊想法的人士透露，皮查伊对布林的参与感到兴奋，并鼓励他做出贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="475" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820792?width=700&amp;height=475" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2012 年，谢尔盖·布林 (Sergey Brin) 与一辆自动驾驶汽车在谷歌山景城总部。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>谷歌在人工智能领域处于领先地位，于 2011 年成立了一个名为 Brain 的研究部门，研究如何使用称为深度学习的计算技术来构建广泛有用的人工智能程序。</p><p> Pichai 今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabets-google-combines-ai-research-units-brain-and-deepmind-620f4f7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将 Brain 团队与 DeepMind 合并</a>，DeepMind 是一家人工智能研究公司，此前在 Alphabet 旗下独立运营。这次改组将 DeepMind 联合创始人哈萨比斯提升为合并后的 Google DeepMind 集团的首席执行官。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，一些研究人员接受了布林的参与，认为这是对他们工作的认可，也是人工智能团队在过渡时期的有益干预。哈萨比斯和许多 Google DeepMind 高管在伦敦工作，使该办公室成为新设置中事实上的权力中心。</p><p>自 11 月份 ChatGPT 发布以来，布林的参与度不断增加。据《纽约时报》早些时候报道的知情人士透露，谷歌的联合创始人参加了会议，审查谷歌正在为 5 月份的开发者大会准备的人工智能产品。</p><p>此后，布林一直在谷歌总部保持着强大的影响力，经常出席研究聚会和公司庆祝活动。谷歌表示，除了联合创始人和董事会成员之外，布林在公司没有正式的新角色。布林的发言人没有回应置评请求。</p><p>佩奇在管理谷歌期间有时是一个隐居的人物，而布林却培养了一个更平易近人的形象，穿着溜冰鞋穿越总部，在公司的各个项目之间穿梭。</p><p>据与布林有过互动的人士透露，自从去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-in-talks-to-invest-200-million-into-ai-startup-11666381180?&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能热潮</a>以来，布林就参加了该公司的发布会，该公司推广了图像生成程序 Stable Diffusion，并且偶尔也会参加在加利福尼亚州希尔斯伯勒一座价值 6800 万美元的豪宅（即 AGI House）举行的活动。 AGI 代表通用人工智能，即计算机程序有一天可以与人类推理相匹配。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="507" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820384?width=700&amp;height=507" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年早些时候，谷歌首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊、谢尔盖·布林、卢森堡首相泽维尔·贝特尔和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢森堡国务部</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年3月，在<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/xavier-bettel_thanks-to-sundar-pichai-and-kent-walker-activity-7041634974231351296-hDnQ/" target="_blank" class="icon none">卢森堡首相访问期间，布林被拍到与皮查伊和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克在谷歌总部合影</a>，布林身着灰色运动裤和黑色长袖衬衫。其他与会者都穿着西装。</p><p>布林与 Gemini 的合作是谷歌长期努力构建人工智能系统的又一成果，这些系统可以展现出类人的能力，并更无缝地满足该公司数十亿用户的需求。</p><p>布林在 2017 年 <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ffvu6Mr1SVc&amp;t=92s" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界经济论坛上接受采访</a>时表示，起初，布林忽视了 Brain 团队的工作，并对他们能否破解人工智能表示怀疑，尽管该团队始于他领导的 Google X 部门。</p><p> “说实话，我根本没有注意它，”布林说。他说，几年后，Brain 的研究被用于谷歌许多最大的产品，颠覆了他之前的假设。</p><p>布林在一定程度上关注了人事问题，随着人工智能研究人员的人才争夺战加剧，这对谷歌和其他大型科技公司来说是一个困难的领域。 2017 年，谷歌发表了一篇具有里程碑意义的论文，该论文被誉为引发了最新一波人工智能发展浪潮，该论文的多位作者已离开该公司，为竞争对手的初创公司筹集数亿美元资金。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>谢尔盖·布林会让谷歌在人工智能领域更具竞争力吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>现任和前任员工表示，尽管布林是世界上最受尊敬的计算机科学家之一，但他需要赶上人工智能的最新发展，并且没有为编码项目做出重大贡献。</p><p>布林在 2018 年发布的上一封股东信中宣传了人工智能的可能性，他写道，“计算解决重要问题的力量和潜力从未如此强大。”</p><p> “人工智能的新春天是我一生中计算领域最重大的发展，”他写道。</p><p>写信给 Miles Kruppa ( <a href="mailto:miles.kruppa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">miles.kruppa@wsj.com)</a>和 Deepa Seetharaman ( <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 14:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e<author><![CDATA[Miles KruppaDeepa Seetharaman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母</category><category>谷歌</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>谢尔盖·布林</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Rise and Fall of the Chief Diversity Officer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着公司优先事项的转变，多元化高管纷纷退出； “一切都是一场战斗” <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820139?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">左起：Melinda Starbird，人力资源和多元化主管；丹尼·门罗 (Dani Monroe)，麻省布里格姆将军医院前任 CDO；和 Yelp 的 CDO 米里亚姆·沃伦 (Miriam Warren)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片插图：Melinda Starbird、Cheryl Richard、Yelp </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/te-ping-chen" itemprop="url" rel="author">：陈德平</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦·韦伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>两年前，首席多元化官是高管队伍中最炙手可热的员工之一。现在，他们越来越感到被冷落。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="">Netflix</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DIS" class="company-name">迪士尼</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="company-name">华纳兄弟探索</a>公司等公司最近表示，备受瞩目的多元化、公平和包容性高管将离职。自去年以来，数千名注重多元化的员工被解雇，一些公司正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-workplace-affirmative-action-dei-3646683b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">缩减</a>种族正义承诺。</p><p>去年秋天科技行业的洗牌期间，许多公司开始重新审视其高管队伍，之后多元化、公平性和包容性（DEI）工作就成为了人们关注的焦点。一些首席多元化官员表示，自从最高法院<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">驳回大学招生中的平权行动</a>以及公司准备迎接<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-attorneys-general-warn-top-u-s-businesses-over-discrimination-1eb78d29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">潜在的法律挑战</a>以来，他们的工作正面临更多审查。 DEI工作也成为了一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantiss-education-policies-leave-florida-teachers-feeling-unsure-3a81a236?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">政治目标</a>。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELP" class="">Yelp</a>首席多元化官米里亚姆·沃伦 (Miriam Warren) 在谈到该<span class="company-name-type">领域</span>高管面临的挑战时表示：“悲伤、非常疲倦，甚至在某些情况下甚至不知所措”。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>在采访中，现任和前任首席多元化官表示，公司高管有时不想改变招聘或晋升流程，尽管最初告诉首席数据官他们被聘用是为了改善人才管道。这种迅速的转变表明，公司对多元化举措的热情并不总是持久的，这让一些多元化官员现在对他们的职业道路产生了质疑。</p><p> 2020 年 5 月，乔治·弗洛伊德 (George Floyd) 在警方拘留期间被谋杀后，各公司纷纷聘请首席多元化官，从而改变了最高管理层的面貌。猎头公司 Russell Reynolds 的一项研究显示，2018 年，标准普尔 500 指数中只有不到一半的公司聘用了该职位，而到 2022 年，四分之三的公司已经设立了该职位。</p><p>曾经主要负责人力资源事务的多元化领导者现在预计将参与新产品开发、营销工作以及影响工人和消费者感受的时事。沃伦和其他 CDO 表示，扩大的职权范围是在政治分裂的环境中实施的，在这种环境中，企业多元化努力经常成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-new-cause-dodging-the-culture-wars-73e52cf3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">社交媒体风暴</a>的主题。</p><h3>需求下降</h3><p>就业数据提供商 Live Data Technologies 的最新分析显示，首席多元化官比人力资源同行更容易受到裁员，其流动率高出 40%。他们找工作的时间也更长。</p><p> “我收到了 300 份申请，然后就停止了追踪，”斯蒂芬妮·鲁宾 (Stephanie Lubin) 说道。5 月份，在线酒类市场 Drizly 被<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a>收购后，她被解雇了，担任该公司多元化主管<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p> Lubin 说，在一个案例中，她为一个没有得到职位的职位经历了 16 轮面试，并表示她现在计划退出 DEI 的工作。<p></p><p> Hanold Associates Executive Search 首席执行官杰森·汉诺德 (Jason Hanold) 表示，去年 CDO 搜索数量下降了 75%，该公司与财富 100 强公司合作，招聘 HR 和 DEI 高管等职位。这是他 30 年来招聘生涯中见过的最低需求。</p><p>他表示，与此同时，越来越多的高管对担任多元化角色感到不安。</p><p> “他们告诉我们，我想要在 DEI 担任另一个角色的唯一方法就是它包含其他内容，”他在谈到对提供更多责任和资源的更广泛头衔的要求时说道。他估计，他目前担任的多元化职位中，有 60% 的职位与其他职位（例如首席人力资源官）结合在一起，而五年前这一比例约为 10%。</p><p>表示，在疫情期间，一些公司将少数族裔员工调入多元化领导层</p>丹尼·门罗，即使他们没有晋级。门罗曾担任麻省总医院布里格姆总医院 (Mass General Brigham) 的首席数据官 (CDO)，该公司是波士顿的一家医院系统，也是该州最大的雇主之一，直至 2021 年，并每年召集 100 多名首席数据官 (CDO) 聚会。<p></p><p> “这些都是下意识的反应，”她在谈到匆忙聘用 CDO 时说道，并补充说其中一些晋升并没有产生太大影响，让双方都感到幻灭。</p><h3>工作中的阻碍</h3><p><a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2023/05/17/diversity-equity-and-inclusion-in-the-workplace/" target="_blank" class="icon none">调查发现</a>，美国工人对于多元化劳动力的重要性存在分歧。</p><p>曾在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/T" class="">AT&amp;T</a>工作过的人力资源和多元化高管梅琳达·斯塔伯德 (Melinda Starbird) 表示，多元化负责人也会遇到高层管理人员的阻碍<span class="company-name-type">，</span></p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">星巴克</a>和 OfferUp（一个在线市场）。领导者有时将多元化努力与任务联系起来，例如适用于联邦承包商的平等就业规则。她说，这些合规要求可能会产生高管阻力，进而渗透到其他文化或政策转变中，例如<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-to-sign-bill-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday-11623944038?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将六月节添加</a>为公司假期。<p></p><p> “即使你向首席执行官汇报，这仍然是一场战斗，而且预算也更少，”Starbird 说，他在 11 月份的一次更广泛的重组中被 OfferUp 解雇。</p><p>许多多元化高管感到缺乏同事的支持。企业领导者网络组织世界 50 集团 (World 50 Group) 今年春天对 138 名多元化高管进行了<a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://world50.com/impact?utm_source=wsj&amp;utm_medium=pr&amp;utm_campaign=2023idreport__;!!F0Stn7g!EGLdSj-lMiFGnMwE-GKlWcgVj1tXMu0_-ZbTIyBUUYuQV0JylSZhtrfPiJ-A4c5JWSBx3Po2kxjQHsQPCw$" target="_blank" class="icon none">一项调查</a>，其中 82% 的人表示他们有足够的影响力来完成工作，比 2022 年下降了 6 个百分点。当被问及是否感受到中层管理人员的支持时，41% 的人表示“是”，下降了 8 个百分点。</p><p>自最高法院于 6 月推翻平权法案以来，企业预计溢出法律诉讼可能会对它们产生影响。罗素雷诺兹多元化、公平和包容性业务全球负责人蒂娜·沙阿·派克戴 (Tina Shah Paikeday) 表示，那些仍在聘用 CDO 的公司希望员工能够帮助董事会应对多元化工作的政治和法律环境，并找出如何采取防御措施来保护自己免受诉讼。</p><p> “他们认识到提前采取行动是明智之举。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820155?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼尔森首席执行官大卫·肯尼表示，重组薪酬以使其更加公平的努力引起了强烈反对。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：尼尔森</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>媒体评级公司尼尔森首席执行官大卫·肯尼表示，当人们担心自己的工作时，无论是因为即将到来的裁员还是人工智能的干扰，他们都会更抵制公司支持的促进多元化的努力。</p><p>肯尼（Kenny）曾担任首席执行官和首席数字官（CDO）， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-executive-or-diversity-chief-nielsens-ceo-is-both-11608908446?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">担任</a>多元化角色以强调多元化对企业未来的重要性。即使作为首席执行官，这也可能是一个艰难的推销。重组薪酬以使其更加公平的努力引起了强烈反对。</p><p> “很多人都在说，‘我正在失去我的那份蛋糕，’”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/9d40dc7b-c819-4785-ab9c-4c1e1272d3a7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给陈德平 ( <a href="mailto:Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com)</a>和劳伦·韦伯 ( <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com)</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bef2e1de-18c2-41e5-86fb-8b21bfe3c1c7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f<author><![CDATA[Te-Ping ChenLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>人力资源咨询</category><category>广播</category><category>有线广播</category><category>会计/咨询</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>商业咨询</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>工作场所多元化</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Netflix</category><category> NFLX</category><category>华特迪士尼</category><category>DIS</category><category>美国电话电报公司</category><category>时间</category><category>华纳兄弟探索公司 A 系列</category><category>世界BD</category><category>华纳兄弟探索公司</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>工作场所多元化</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人力资源咨询</category><category>广播</category><category>有线广播</category><category>会计</category><category>咨询</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>商业咨询</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Where Is Kamala Harris?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>拜登 2024 年竞选活动开局缓慢，副总统支持率低<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071890"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821223?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">副总统卡玛拉·哈里斯上个月在北卡罗来纳州夏洛特发表了关于堕胎权利的演讲。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Erik S. Lesser/PRESS POOL </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071890"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/catherine-lucey" itemprop="url" rel="author">凯瑟琳·露西</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 5:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>副总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kamala-harris">卡玛拉·哈里斯</a>计划为拜登总统的连任<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kamala-harris-prepares-to-hit-the-road-for-biden-despite-cracks-in-her-support-45a4015d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">进行广泛的竞选活动</a>，但她的早期日程表明情况并非如此。</p><p>根据副总统的日历，在拜登发起竞选活动后的 10 周内，这位副总统已前往 9 个州（其中三个州被视为 2024 年大选的战场），并出席了 7 场筹款活动。</p><p>拜登的竞选团队表示，哈里斯早期的竞选节奏与2011年拜登担任副总统时的情况类似。在此期间，拜登总统在全国各地参加了大致相似数量的竞选活动。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6D4E88DA-6C2C-4F8E-903E-A5D7F614F8C1&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwhere-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》的肯·托马斯 (Ken Thomas) 详细分析了 2020 年以来政治格局的变化以及拜登总统在 2024 年将面临的挑战。图片说明：Ryan Trefes<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>竞选发言人凯文·穆尼奥斯（Kevin Munoz）表示：“虽然历史表明，现任总统竞选竞选还为时过早，但副总统哈里斯已经在做与全国选民会面和接触的重要工作。”<br><br>竞选团队指出，她本月访问了亚利桑那州，并且她的行程正在增加。周五，她计划前往佛罗里达州。</p><p>一些竞选捐助者对她的能力表示保留，并表示她没有拜登那样的吸引力，一位筹款人形容她“很难推销”。</p><p> “仅就我自己而言，我认为以她为主角的筹款活动不可能非常成功，”民主党捐助者兼审判律师约翰摩根说。 “首先，对于包括民主党人在内的许多人来说，她是两极分化的。”</p><p>共和党人试图强调副总统的弱点。共和党全国委员会在推特上指出了演讲中的失误。前南卡罗来纳州州长妮基·黑利 (Nikki Haley) 目前在 2024 年共和党总统提名竞选中的民意支持率为个位数，她认为投票给拜登实际上就是投票给哈里斯。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为卡马拉·哈里斯如何为拜登总统的连任竞选做出最好的贡献？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “我们的对手是卡马拉·哈里斯。毫不掩饰这一点，”她在最近接受福克斯新闻采访时说道。</p><p>许多民主党人认为这种攻击对第一位担任副总统的黑人女性不公平，并指出她是堕胎等民主党核心问题的有效传播者，也是女性、黑人选民和年轻人中受欢迎的人物。这反映在她的日程安排中，其中包括有关堕胎和枪支暴力的演讲。</p><p> “本届政府中没有人比副总统在堕胎问题上更引人注目、更真实，也更有说服力，”纳拉尔支持堕胎美国组织主席米尼·蒂玛拉朱 (Mini Timmaraju) 说。 “我们对她的到来感到高兴。我完全期待看到更多。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821651?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>其他民主党人希望看到她在选民中的支持率上升，这样她就可以成为总统更有效的代理人，而总统自己的民意调查数字一直稳定但较低。 They say that could be important as the campaign heats up: At 80 years old, Biden could face limitations in the amount of campaigning he can do. Harris is 58 years old.</p><p> Harris has an approval rating of around 40%, according to the FiveThirtyEight average of national polls, a similar rating to Biden&#39;s.</p><p> During the campaign&#39;s first 10 weeks, there were 30 days in which there were no public events on the vice president&#39;s schedule, many of those weekend days. The vice president&#39;s office said that there were activities not reflected on her schedule on some of those days, largely private meetings or press interviews.</p><p> Christine Sinicki, who chairs the Democratic Party of Milwaukee County, which includes the city of Milwaukee, said she wasn&#39;t worried that Harris hadn&#39;t traveled to Wisconsin yet. But she noted that Biden narrowly won the state in 2020. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821220?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Vice President Kamala Harris participating in a Martin Luther King Jr. Day service project in Washington, DC, in January.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Leigh Vogel/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We need to make sure we are doing everything we can to get those votes out,” she said, adding that Harris is popular there, particularly with women, including those among minorities. “We need to see the vice president here. Especially in places like Milwaukee.”</p><p> North Carolina Democratic Gov. Roy Cooper, who hosted Harris for a speech on abortion in June, said Harris had been to the state seven times since Biden was elected. “We&#39;re glad for every visit. And I think she&#39;s helping to make a real difference showing North Carolinians how the Biden-Harris administration is working for them,” he said.</p><p> The political-action committee Emily&#39;s List has begun airing a TV ad aimed at boosting Harris. The ad, also funded by the pro-Biden super PAC Future Forward, features Harris speaking about Republican efforts to restrict abortion access.</p><p> Democratic strategist Mary Anne Marsh said such efforts will be crucial for Harris. “They need to raise her favorability ratings so she&#39;s more effective as this goes on,” she said.</p><p> Some donors are expressing enthusiasm for Harris. Charles Myers, who hosted an event headlined by Harris in New York recently, told the room, “I will be very proud to be the first one to sign up for Harris for President 2028.”</p><p> So far, it appears that Harris&#39;s campaign efforts are suffering from some of the same trouble other vice presidents have faced in the job: making clear what it is, exactly, that they do.</p><p> The No. 2 doesn&#39;t set the White House agenda and can&#39;t publicly get ahead of Biden on policy or be seen as outshining him, Harris allies said. The same could be said for the campaign trail.</p><p> “The lesson you learn when you&#39;re in the office of the vice president is it is very difficult to win a battle about what she is doing,” said Matt Bennett, a former aide to Vice President Al Gore and co-founder of Third Way, a centrist think tank.</p><p> Write to Catherine Lucey at <a href="mailto:catherine.lucey@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">catherine.lucey@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408<author><![CDATA[Catherine Lucey]]></author><category> Abortion</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Medical Treatments/Procedures</category><category>选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Kamala Harris</category><category>流产</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>medical treatments</category><category>程序</category><category>选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Jackie O.’s Collection of Homes Was as Iconic as It Gets]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A massive East Hampton estate. A sprawling New York City apartment. The properties where she lived before and after becoming first lady are some of the most coveted real estate in America <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818403/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, pictured in 1960, lived in an iconic collection of luxury homes." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, pictured in 1960, lived in an iconic collection of luxury homes. The Estate of Jacques Lowe/Getty Images <span>The Estate of Jacques Lowe/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055379"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055379"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eb-solomont" itemprop="url" rel="author">EB Solomont</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 21, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-o-s-collection-of-homes-was-as-iconic-as-it-gets-2500daf4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> When Eaddo and Peter D. Kiernan III first laid eyes on Hammersmith Farm in Newport, RI, in the 1990s, they loved it immediately.</p><p> Immortalized as the site of the 1953 wedding reception of Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy and John F. Kennedy, and later dubbed President Kennedy&#39;s summer White House, the circa-1880s estate overlooking Narragansett Bay hadn&#39;t been lived in for decades. But Kiernan, a self-described patriot who said he knew the late John F. Kennedy Jr. , realized instantly it would be the perfect summer home for his own sprawling Irish Catholic family.</p><p> The Kiernans purchased Hammersmith Farm for just over $8 million in 1999, and then spent more than 10 years restoring it, drawing on old sketches, photographs and stories shared by Jackie&#39;s stepbrother, Hugh D. “Yusha” Auchincloss III, whose family built the estate about a century before. “We would literally say, &#39;Tell us everything you can remember,&#39; ” said Kiernan, a former Goldman Sachs banker. When Auchincloss saw the finished renovation, Kiernan said, he wept. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="534" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820716?width=700&amp;height=534" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hammersmith Farm, in Newport, RI</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carol M. Highsmith/Buyenlarge/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “There are pretty houses in the Hamptons and in Nantucket, but we wanted to do something that was authentically connected to what had gone on here for a very long time,” Kiernan said.</p><p> Born into wealth, Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis lived in homes ranging from apartments in New York City to houses in Georgetown and estates in Newport, Virginia and Martha&#39;s Vineyard. Many were legacy properties that, nearly 30 years after Jackie&#39;s death, still command top-dollar among luxury buyers drawn to their classical style, history and aesthetic.</p><p> In Washington, DC, real-estate agent Jamie Peva of Washington Fine Properties said homes tied to Jackie and John Kennedy can command a roughly 10% premium even in Georgetown, a historic neighborhood full of notable residents. “It might be a conversation starter that [former Secretary of State Henry] Kissinger lived there, but it doesn&#39;t translate into money unless it&#39;s the Kennedys,” he said.<br><br> Peva said it helps that the couple—along with their families and later, Jackie herself—owned exceptional homes in prime locations. “The house they went to the White House from was one of the most important houses in Georgetown,” Peva said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="722" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818423?width=700&amp;height=722" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Kennedys, pictured in 1961, lived in Georgetown before moving to the White House.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bettmann Archive/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Jackie&#39;s name is an instant draw and marketing boon, said Eileen O&#39;Neill of the Corcoran Group, who is marketing Lasata, one of her childhood homes in the Hamptons, for $55 million. But provenance only goes so far, O&#39;Neill said, and Lasata&#39;s classic elegance and exacting renovations by the recent owners have drawn interest from potential buyers. “Comparable sales and the climate of the market is really what dictates price,” she said.</p><p> That was the case when Jackie&#39;s childhood apartment at 740 Park Avenue in Manhattan sold for $25.25 million in 2017, said Jeremy Stein of Sotheby&#39;s International Realty, who was involved in the deal. The buyer was banking heir Jacob M. Safra, records show. “The building speaks for itself,” said Stein, citing location, architecture and a long history of prominent residents, including Jackie. “It remains this iconic, great building that has a cachet, but it lives up to the cachet,” he said.</p><p> Read on for a closer look at notable properties tied to Jackie over the years, based on property records, multiple biographies and the accounts of real-estate agents. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/0c296686-a760-4b9d-a314-09cc321612ca-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> As a young child, Jackie spent summers at a lavish East Hampton estate owned by her paternal grandfather, John Vernou Bouvier Jr. Known as Lasata, meaning “place of peace” in the Algonquin language of the native Montaukett people, the estate sat on roughly 14 acres. It was set back from Further Lane and had a long, curving drive and 15-room manor built in the 1910s, according to the book “Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis: A Life” by Donald Spoto. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="511" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818420?width=639&amp;height=511" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie, left, spent summers in East Hampton in homes owned by her grandparents.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bettmann Archive/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> When designer Reed Krakoff and his wife, interior designer Delphine Krakoff, bought the property in 2007, the manor hadn&#39;t been renovated in years, Reed Krakoff said. The Krakoffs paid $25 million for two parcels totaling about 11 acres, records show. The couple spent nearly two years restoring the house, using building techniques and materials original to the home, he said. They restored single-pane glass windows and instead of sheetrock walls they used three-coat plaster on metal lathe. They also refurbished and restored all of the existing hardware and fixtures, he said. (For example, the bathtubs are porcelain over iron.)</p><p> Krakoff said there is a “mystique” to owning a famous property, but the real draw was the house itself. “It&#39;s a really rare thing to find a beautiful, historic house that hasn&#39;t been altered in a way that takes away from the authenticity,” he said. The couple, who have restored around 15 homes, uncovered and restored original oak-paneled walls from the Bouviers&#39; time under Louis XV-style paneling added later. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/019dae13-6292-447b-ba02-4bbb620702e5.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Around 2017, the Krakoffs subdivided the property and sold it in two parts. A neighbor purchased a nearly 4-acre parcel with a sunken tennis court for $11.25 million. David Zander, a television, commercial and film producer based in Los Angeles, paid $24 million in 2018 for a roughly 7.2-acre parcel comprising the main house, a swimming pool, pool house, guesthouse, caretaker&#39;s cottage and a garage with a workshop.</p><p> Zander said the scale, proportion and aesthetics of the home drew him in—not the Jackie connection. “If Jackie lived in a hovel would I be interested in buying it? No,” he said. But he admitted that over time, the connection became interesting. “Through a house, you become a small part of American history,” he said. Zander said he has repaired structural issues and made other improvements to the home, including adding a glass front door so that visitors can see through the house to the garden.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-os-childhood-hamptons-home-lists-for-55-million-8187989c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">The property</a> also has a visual easement in front to maintain a view of the house from the street. “It&#39;s a significant historical structure for all to enjoy,” Zander said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/da99f27d-8cc1-479d-a3b0-40bff490d707-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> When she wasn&#39;t at Lasata, Jackie and her parents summered at Wildmoor, a circa-1800s house in East Hampton owned by her paternal grandfather, who let his son and daughter-in-law stay there rent-free, according to multiple accounts. The house, located a few houses down from Grey Gardens, the famed estate once owned by Jackie&#39;s cousins, was a “charming old wooden-frame structure, clapboarded and shingled, with a widow&#39;s walk overlooking acres of potato fields, a cattail swamp, and the distant, roaring Atlantic,” according to John H. Davis&#39; 1993 book “The Kennedys: Dynasty and Disaster.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="909" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818419?width=700&amp;height=909" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie and her parents lived rent-free at Wildmoor, which was owned by her grandfather.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bettmann Archive/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Later, the abstract expressionist Adolph Gottlieb and his wife, Esther Gottlieb, purchased Wildmoor and turned a free-standing carriage house into an art studio. Around 1990, the attorney Richard D. Spizzirri purchased the property; his estate sold it for $6.8 million in 2021, records show. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/ac9e37b1-b5b9-4344-9f66-72586e6c854d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> David Tosher, a residential design consultant who advised the buyer, said the roughly 5,700-square-foot house with six bedrooms hadn&#39;t been renovated in decades. The wood on the bottom of the house was rotten from sitting in mud for decades and “the house was held there by the grace of God,” he said. The kitchen was “uneatable,” a glass atrium was leaking and at some point, portions of the elevator shaft were blocked off and removed, rendering it useless, he said. Tosher said workers took apart the house and rebuilt it entirely in a slightly different location farther from the road. They kept the original framing but added a full basement. They also used old photographs to restore original features including the main staircase, some doors and a gooseneck-curved railing. “We rebuilt everything but left the history,” Tosher said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/30ae4b25-5ebc-42d2-9413-17f5d1421fa2-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> As a child in the 1930s, Jackie lived with her parents at 740 Park Avenue, an elegant, limestone-clad building designed by Rosario Candela. The building was developed by Jackie&#39;s maternal grandfather, James T. Lee, who let his daughter, Janet Lee Bouvier, and son-in-law, John Vernou “Black Jack” Bouvier III, live there rent-free, according to multiple accounts.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Flamboyant but cash-strapped, Jackie&#39;s father gutted the kitchen and added gold-plated fixtures to the bathroom, according to Michael Gross&#39; “740 Park: The Story of the World&#39;s Richest Apartment Building.” But his finances were such that he couldn&#39;t afford to furnish it when he was done, leaving open space for Jackie and her sister to roller-skate through what became one of New York City&#39;s most iconic buildings, according to the book.</p><p> Today the apartment is owned by Jacob M. Safra, an heir to a banking fortune, who purchased it for $25.25 million in 2017, records show. The sellers, hedge funder David Ganek and his wife, Danielle Ganek, renovated the duplex and had it on the market for several years, asking as much as $44 million in 2014.</p><p> Stein of Sotheby&#39;s, who represented the seller, said the Kennedy and Bouvier cachet is real although the building itself is the main draw for most buyers. “The building speaks for itself,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/f82f3f77-7910-4471-a9fa-c600419fd530-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Jackie moved to Merrywood in the 1940s after her mother married Standard Oil heir Hugh D. Auchincloss Jr., according to Spoto&#39;s “A Life.” Located on the banks of the Potomac River, the estate is about 8 miles from downtown Washington with a Georgian-style house spanning more than 16,000 square feet.</p><p> By the 1960s, Auchincloss, facing financial constraints, agreed to sell Merrywood, then spanning about 46 acres, for $650,000 to real-estate developers and brothers Sheldon and Ira Magazine, according to Jan Pottker&#39;s 2002 book “Janet and Jackie: The Story of a Mother and Her Daughter, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.” The Magazine brothers&#39; plans to build 1,030 high-rise apartments on the site sparked “an enormous cry” among neighbors, the book said. After the deal went through in 1963, the Kennedy White House took steps to block the high-rise development. “Jackie sparked it,” said the book, citing her commitment to preservation and environmental causes. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="553" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818405?width=700&amp;height=553" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie lived at Merrywood, pictured in 1962, following her mother&#39;s marriage to owner Hugh D. Auchincloss Jr.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ASSOCIATED PRESS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In 1965, the Magazine brothers sold the entire property for $650,000 to real-estate developer C. Wyatt Dickerson and his then-wife, Nancy Dickerson, who retained the main residence and more than 7 acres and built about 46 smaller homes on the remaining land, according to “Janet and Jackie.” In 2005, AOL co-founder Steve Case bought the 7-acre original manor residence for a then-record sum of $24.5 million, records show. Thirteen years later, he sold it for $43 million to the Kingdom Saudi Arabia, the government of which expressed “tremendous respect” for the home&#39;s place in American history in a statement at the time.</p><p> Marc C. Lowham of TTR Sotheby&#39;s International Realty, who was involved in the 2018 deal, said the property&#39;s location and provenance made it one of the most timeless and valuable estates in the area. Many original details remain, including the basic floor plan and elaborate plaster moldings. The gated estate also has formal gardens, a swimming pool and tennis court. “The Jackie Kennedy legacy there still feels very much alive,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/5880d3e8-cd01-470a-a46e-56bfd86537af-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In 1953, Jackie and John Kennedy&#39;s 1,200-person wedding reception took place at Hammersmith Farm, an estate overlooking Narragansett Bay in Newport, RI The Auchincloss family estate had gardens designed by Frederick Law Olmsted, according to “A Life.” During the summer of 1961, when the Kennedys visited Hammersmith, the farm was dubbed “the summer White House” by the press, according to “Janet and Jackie.”</p><p> The White House installed phones in the main house and the Coast Guard inspected all boats and ships sailing past, the book said. After the oil crisis of the 1970s, Jackie&#39;s mother, Janet Auchincloss, sold the main house and about 54 acres for about $825,000 and the property was turned into a museum, the book said.</p><p> When plans to rezone the property and build condos emerged in the 1990s, William F. Farley, a Rhode Island native and former CEO of Fruit of the Loom, swooped in and paid $6.675 million in 1997, records show. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818413?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie and John Kennedy&#39;s 1953 wedding reception took place at Hammersmith Farm, an Auchincloss-owned estate in Newport, RI</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sygma/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818410?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Kennedys, pictured in 1962, had an office at Hammersmith.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sygma/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “My motivation was really simple,” he said. “It was to make sure it wouldn&#39;t get developed and it would remain part of American history.” Farley kept it as a museum, and sold it a few years later to Kiernan on the condition that Hammersmith would never be developed commercially. Kiernan paid just over $8 million, records show.</p><p> Kiernan said there was work to be done. “No one had lived here for a quarter-century,” he said. The Kiernans reinforced the structure with steel and wood beams, replaced the roof and redid the plumbing and electrical. They removed parking lots and restored farmland, and today Hammersmith is a working farm with horses, llamas and other animals; an old tea house has been repurposed as an aviary for peacocks, Kiernan said.</p><p> Kiernan said the Auchincloss family was “incredibly gracious” and gave him a portrait of Kennedy that is hanging in his office—which he was told Kennedy also used. The Kiernans, who purchased some of the home&#39;s original furniture at auction, have since held reunions at Hammersmith, he said. Kiernan said when he was working on Wall Street, the farm was like a “tonic” that would calm him. Two of his daughters have gotten married there, and the family feels a sense of responsibility for it. “We&#39;re trustees of it more than anything,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/c35c58ed-3b19-46c9-a634-d14f37262157-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> About three years after getting married, Jackie and John Kennedy bought a house in Hyannis Port that became part of the famous Kennedy compound. The couple paid $45,948 for the shingled house, located next to homes owned by John Kennedy&#39;s parents, Rose and Joe Kennedy, and his brother Robert F. Kennedy&#39;s home, records show. Built around 1925, Jackie and John Kennedy&#39;s house has about 4,484 square feet of interior space and sits on about 0.81 acres, according to the Barnstable County assessor. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3d2181e5-f058-4467-aecf-86900af4d845.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Spanning about 6 acres of waterfront, the compound was a base for Kennedy&#39;s presidential campaign. After the 1960 election, “the grass in front of Jack&#39;s deck became the temporary stage for twice-daily press conferences for the next couple of weeks,” according to Kate Storey&#39;s book “White House By the Sea: A Century of the Kennedys at Hyannis Port.” It remained a summer White House and presidential retreat until Kennedy&#39;s assassination in 1963, according to the National Park Service.</p><p> In 2004, Jackie&#39;s daughter, Caroline Kennedy, and son-in-law, Edwin Schlossberg, sold the house for $3 million to a Kennedy family trust, records show.  It is currently used as a summer residence by Ted Kennedy Jr. and his wife, Katherine “Kiki” Kennedy, who remodeled the house and donated the original windows, cabinets and shingles to the John F. Kennedy Hyannis Museum, according to Wendy Northcross, the museum&#39;s executive director. The museum allowed local artists to repurpose the materials into artifacts and other works of art. <strong>&nbsp;</strong> The house is currently worth around $4.5 million, according to Zillow&#39;s “Zestimate.” In 2012, Rose and Joe Kennedy&#39;s home—known as the Big House—was donated to the Edward M. Kennedy Institute for the US Senate to be preserved. “This house was my family&#39;s epicenter,” Ted Kennedy Jr. said at the time. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/353f6970-acc1-491f-bed2-2a6632e698b3-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In 1957, before Kennedy&#39;s run for president, he and the future first lady bought their first house together, a red brick Federal-style building on N Street in Georgetown. “Kennedy paid $82,000 for it, and Jackie&#39;s remodeling cost another $18,000,” according to “A Life.” She filled the house with Louis XV armchairs and porcelains, Louis XVI dining chairs and an antique carpet. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/6df2da95-261d-4182-8d6b-21e5eb6afd0b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Following Kennedy&#39;s assassination in 1963, Jackie returned to Georgetown, where she bought a 1790s house that is currently listed on the National Register of Historic Places.</p><p> She paid about $175,000 for it, but moved to New York about a year later to escape the barrage of tourists that gathered outside, according to “A Life.” Yolande Betbeze Fox, a onetime Miss America, bought the house in 1976, records show. Construction entrepreneur David W. Hudgens purchased it for $5.25 million in 2017. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/86ad8303-f95c-4b8d-a0cf-faab53debfc2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Before buying Fox&#39;s house, Hudgens purchased two adjacent properties for $1.2 million and $1.625 million, records show. Once he owned the trio, he tapped architect Dale Overmyer to combine the properties into a mansion that is more than 15,300 square feet and has 13 bedrooms.</p><p> Overmyer said Hudgens had a passage built underneath the homes to connect them. Certain features of the former Kennedy home remain, including a wood-paneled library and dining room with gold leaf ceiling. The fireplaces—saved from a dumpster by Overmyer—are also original.</p><p> Following Hudgens&#39;s death in 2022, the assemblage of houses came on the market for $26.5 million this year. It is currently priced at $19.5 million, according to Zillow. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d9e069f1-5b2f-4564-92c0-54714ba10634-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Leaving Washington after Kennedy&#39;s death, Jackie purchased a 14-room apartment at 1040 Fifth Avenue, overlooking Central Park and the Metropolitan Museum of Art. “The arrangements for the apartment at 1040 Fifth were made so quietly that her name did not appear on the contract,” according to “Janet and Jackie,” which said she paid roughly $200,000 for the apartment, which spans the entire 15th floor. Jackie furnished the apartment with antique furniture and art, and lived there until her death in 1994, the book said.</p><p> The following year, the late billionaire David Koch purchased the apartment for $9.2 million, according to C. David Heymann&#39;s book “American Legacy: The Story of John and Caroline Kennedy,” published in 2008. “Mrs. Onassis was very conservative financially, and she didn&#39;t spend much on it,” Koch later told the Observer. “We gutted the apartment and redid everything.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="488" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818401?width=700&amp;height=488" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie, on Fifth Avenue in 1964, moved to New York to avoid publicity in Washington, DC</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>In 2006, Koch sold the apartment for $30 million to hedge funder Glenn Dubin and his wife, Eva Dubin, records show.</p><p> Although luxury buyers have more options than ever, including new condominiums, 1040 Fifth is still considered one of the city&#39;s best buildings, said Deborah Grubman of the Corcoran Group, who was involved in the 2006 sale. She said Jackie&#39;s celebrity status bolstered sales prices after she died—“She had some fake pearls that went for crazy numbers also,” Grubman said—but the building&#39;s attributes stand on their own. “Nobody did an apartment better than they did in those days,” she said. “The view is still something that&#39;s hard to duplicate.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1380" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/6d3a48b2-8040-4709-941e-f2a338e85920-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In 1978, Jackie bought over 300 acres of land on the tip of Martha&#39;s Vineyard where she built a secluded summer residence known as Red Gate Farm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818424?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie purchased more than 300 acres on Martha&#39;s Vineyard where she built a summer retreat.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brooks Kraft/Sygma/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> After paying just over $1 million for the land, Jackie tapped architect Hugh Newell Jacobsen to design the shingled Cape Cod saltbox-style main house and a two-story guesthouse, which cost about $3.1 million and was completed in 1981, according to “A Life.” Philanthropist and horticulturist Rachel “Bunny” Mellon, who designed the White House Rose Garden when Jackie was first lady, designed the landscapes.</p><p> Over the years, Jackie hosted President Bill Clinton and others at the home, but she also clashed with a group of the Wampanoag Native Americans, who claimed the right to access a beachfront area on her property. (She settled the dispute in 1990.)</p><p> After Jackie&#39;s death, her daughter, Caroline Kennedy, and son-in-law, Edwin Schlossberg, enlisted Deborah Berke, dean of the Yale School of Architecture, to head up a multimillion-dollar renovation of the property, which also includes a pool, a tennis court and a treehouse Jackie built for her grandchildren. Caroline Kennedy listed it for sale in 2019, asking $65 million. At the time, she said in a statement that her three children had grown and it was time for the family to “spread its wings.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          edgetoedge
"><figure class="media-object-image img-edgetoedge"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818505?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> She paid about $1 million for the land and built a house that was completed in 1981.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Christie&#39;s International Real Estate</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In 2020 and 2021, however, two conservation groups—the Martha&#39;s Vineyard Land Bank Commission and Sheriff&#39;s Meadow Foundation—bought the land in separate transactions totaling $37 million, the groups said. The family retained roughly 60 acres, including the residence.</p><p> “Many of these land conservation efforts take decades to achieve,” said Adam Moore, president of Sheriff&#39;s Meadow Foundation, who described the deal as “the pinnacle of my career in conservation.” The groups are currently seeking permits to open the property, now known as Squibnocket Pond Reservation, to the public. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/b46c7859-e02b-424e-bc15-d0b3c7548cc6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> During the last decades of her life, Jackie retreated to a country home in New Jersey where she could ride horses. Located in Bernardsville, NJ, the property cost about $200,000 in 1974 and included a “two-story frame house on 10 acres of lush hunt country,” according to “A Life.” Jackie painted the outside yellow with white trim, the book said. “Inside, she furnished it with comfortable, chintz-covered country pieces.”</p><p> After she died, then-Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey said Jackie adopted Bernardsville “in pursuit of that elusive privacy” that she sought for much of her life. “There she indulged in her favorite pastime of horseback riding,” he said, in a memorial tribute shared with Congress.</p><p> In 1997, Caroline Kennedy and her brother, John F. Kennedy Jr., sold the property to their mother&#39;s former neighbor, Marjorie “Peggy” McDonnell Walsh for $1.475 million, records show.</p><p> “We tore down the house and built a new one,” Walsh said, declining to share details about the new house. “It doesn&#39;t matter,” she said. “The much more important thing is we both love the property. It&#39;s a private valley. It&#39;s beautiful.”</p><p> Write to EB Solomont at <a href="mailto:eb.solomont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eb.solomont@wsj.com</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Which of Jackie Kennedy&#39;s properties do you think is the most iconic?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-os-collection-of-homes-was-as-iconic-as-it-gets-2500daf4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-os-collection-of-homes-was-as-iconic-as-it-gets-2500daf4<author><![CDATA[E.B. Solomont]]></author><category> wsjmansion</category><category> photo-research</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>Construction</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>家居与园艺</category><category>home &amp; garden</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Thank Tesla: The Biggest Obstacle to EV Ownership Will Soon Be History]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> As Ford, GM, Volvo, Mercedes-Benz and other automakers migrate to Tesla&#39;s vast and growing Supercharger network, the knock-on effects are a big win for all EV buyers, says Dan Neil <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001036339"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-813675?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> OPEN FOR BUSINESS Last year Tesla announced a deal with the Biden administration to open part of its Supercharger network. The plan calls for at least 3,500 new or existing Superchargers to be publicly accessible along major highways.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tesla </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001036339"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-neil"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BQ140_DANNEI_AM_20180906155439.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-neil" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dan Neil</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 20, 2023 5:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thank-tesla-the-biggest-obstacle-to-ev-ownership-will-soon-be-history-dc9945be"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <strong>ON WEDNESDAY</strong> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">Tesla</a> announced its second-quarter results, chalking up another season of record sales, staggering profits and breakneck expansion for the American electric carmaker. This year, in a watershed for electric mobility, the Tesla Model Y became the bestselling automobile in the world. As an advocate for better cars may I extend a hearty booyah.</p><p> Underscoring Tesla&#39;s rout, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="">Ford</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> GM, Rivian, Volvo, Polestar and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MBGYY" class="company-name">Mercedes-Benz</a> have announced plans to adopt Tesla&#39;s North American Charging Standard, making it possible for their products to access Tesla&#39;s vast and growing network of Supercharger stations.</p><p> The generalization of NACS will be a huge win for consumers who have both wanted and feared buying their first electric car due to the inadequacy of existing CCS-based infrastructure. NACS will soon bring a generation of short-winded, slow-charging EVs within the radius of a Supercharger station somewhere, anywhere. Suddenly, buying an EV other than a Tesla doesn&#39;t seem so crazy. If the price is right. And by right, I mean much, <em>much</em> cheaper. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> NACS may be the proverbial camel&#39;s nose, as the industry migrates to Tesla-like architecture. <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p> The timing depends. Ford said its products would gain access to 12,000 Superchargers in North America by early 2024. For these non-NACS vehicles, Tesla has developed what it calls the Magic Dock adapter, allowing Superchargers to grok CCS-equipped vehicles. This plastic coupler is secured to the charger, ready when needed.</p><p> It&#39;s not clear to what extent CCS-equipped cars can take advantage of NACS higher charging rates, currently capped at 250 kW, with 350 kW (V4) being tested. These limitations would be on the car side, having to do with capacity of the power electronics, the charging conditions and mood of the battery-management system. NACS may be the proverbial camel&#39;s nose, as the rest of the industry inevitably migrates to Tesla-like electrical architecture and codeware, in the interests of compatibility. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-813688?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> EVOLUTION ROAD This year GM, Ford, Mercedes-Benz and others announced they would adopt Tesla&#39;s North American Charging Standard, allowing their vehicles to charge at Tesla Superchargers without adapters.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tesla</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Starting in 2025, Ford&#39;s EV products—including Mustang Mach-E and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2022-ford-f-150-lightning-review-11652388946?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">F-150 Lightning pickup</a> —will adopt the NACS port. Other automakers are considering a combination charge-port, accommodating the legacy CCS plug as well as Tesla&#39;s notably slimmer and easier-to-handle, um, handle.</p><p> Other challenges are more administrative. Fumble-free automatic billing is one of the glories of the Supercharger network. Tesla&#39;s Superchargers haven&#39;t previously needed input screens or card readers. Last year Tesla announced a deal with the White House to open 3,500 new or existing Supercharger stations to the public along major highways. However, in order to be eligible for federal incentives, public Superchargers need to have some point-of-sale interface.</p><p> Apart from charging, consumers&#39; biggest issue with EVs has been affordability. In a Cox Automotive survey, 51% of respondents said they were interested in buying an EV. 43% said they were holding off due to high prices. Meanwhile, a fleet of highly hyped mass-market EVs (Ford Mustang Mach-E, Ford F-150 Lightning, VW ID.4, Cadillac Lyriq) are nailed to the showroom floors. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-813677?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> PLUG AND PLAY Tesla has more than 17,000 Superchargers in the US and 45,000 worldwide. Charging rates are capped at 250 kW (V3 charging), which can restore up to 200 miles of range in 15 minutes. The company is developing V4 charging, with charging rates as high as 350 kW.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tesla</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The NACS standard is another sign to the informed buyer that the choice is between two kinds of EVs: Tesla and anything else. It&#39;s past time legacy carmakers&#39; prices reflect this two-tiered, varsity/JV reality. They should mark down, and write off, their first uncompetitive drafts of EV history and get on with the second. Pre-NACS inventory such as the ID.4, the Mach-E, Lightning and Lyriq should get a major price haircut. As for the dozens of CCS-equipped EVs heading to the US in the next year, I encourage car buyers to go Sweeney Todd on them. The price correction is at hand.</p><p> In something of a poignant coincidence, this week Ford announced a nearly $10,000 price cut on the F-150 Lightning the day before the first production Tesla Cybertruck rolled off the line.</p><p> Most importantly, NACS will make my job easier. I have felt ridiculous repeating automakers&#39; range and charging estimates, knowing that the range represents the rosiest of forecasts in the balmiest of conditions, and the maximum charging rate presupposes a device so rare it might as well be folklore. At the end of the rainbow, m&#39;lad, there&#39;s an Electrify America charger putting out 350 kW. Shoor there is. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> MORE IN RUMBLE SEAT</h4><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2024-rolls-royce-spectre-review-electrified-at-last-45414642?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2024 Rolls-Royce Spectre: Electrified at Last</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2024-dodge-hornet-r-t-review-an-italian-stallion-made-for-america-ecd3ff48?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2024 Dodge Hornet R/T: An Italian Stallion, Made for America</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2023-range-rover-phev-review-a-hybrid-worth-plugging-in-1a4d7990?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2023 Range Rover PHEV: A Hybrid Worth Plugging In</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2023-maserati-grecale-modena-review-dont-call-it-a-comeback-yet-20f83ef0?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2023 Maserati Grecale Modena: Don&#39;t Call It a Comeback Yet</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/porsche-911-reimagined-by-singer-review-posher-than-ever-9f5049ca?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Porsche 911 Reimagined by Singer: Posher Than Ever</a></li></ul></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 21:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/thank-tesla-the-biggest-obstacle-to-ev-ownership-will-soon-be-history-dc9945be</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/thank-tesla-the-biggest-obstacle-to-ev-ownership-will-soon-be-history-dc9945be<author><![CDATA[Dan Neil]]></author><category>下班</category><category>机动车</category><category>乘用车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>Sales Figures</category><categor